  {
    "text": "The paper's claim that RLHF embeds the dynamics of the dominant social order explicitly restricts this occurrence to scenarios where the reward model is trained on human feedback from a population with a single dominant group.",
    "topic": "Scope of embedding claim"
  },
  {
    "text": "In the paper, the phrase 'dominant social order' is defined as the set of norms and power relations maintained by whiteness in a white-dominant society.",
    "topic": "Definition of dominant social order"
  },
  {
    "text": "The study's demonstration of embedding relies on empirical results from RLHF systems where the human evaluators were predominantly white.",
    "topic": "Empirical basis of demonstration"
  },
  {
    "text": "The paper presents a theoretical framework that predicts embedding of any dominant social order, but only provides evidence for whiteness-as-governance cases.",
    "topic": "Generality of theoretical framework"
  }
]
